{'bozo': False,
 'encoding': 'utf-8',
 'entries': [{'author': 'Sarah Abderemane',
              'author_detail': {'name': 'Sarah Abderemane'},
              'authors': [{'name': 'Sarah Abderemane'}],
              'guidislink': False,
              'id': 'https://www.djangoproject.com/weblog/2026/mar/08/dsf-member-of-the-month-theresa-seyram-agbenyegah/',
              'link': 'https://www.djangoproject.com/weblog/2026/mar/08/dsf-member-of-the-month-theresa-seyram-agbenyegah/',
              'links': [{'href': 'https://www.djangoproject.com/weblog/2026/mar/08/dsf-member-of-the-month-theresa-seyram-agbenyegah/',
                         'rel': 'alternate',
                         'type': 'text/html'}],
              'published': 'Sun, 08 Mar 2026 00:00:00 -0600',
              'published_parsed': time.struct_time(tm_year=2026, tm_mon=3, tm_mday=8, tm_hour=6, tm_min=0, tm_sec=0, tm_wday=6, tm_yday=67, tm_isdst=0),
              'summary': '<p>For March 2026, we welcome Theresa Seyram '
                         'Agbenyegah as our DSF member of the month! ⭐</p>\n'
                         '<p><img alt="Theresa portrait, a pretty black woman '
                         'with short hair. She is looking at the camera with a '
                         'big smile. She wears a white t-shirt with written in '
                         'green &quot;Django Girls Koforidua&quot;. The '
                         'background is blurry but really colorful with shades '
                         'of green and orange." '
                         'src="https://media.djangoproject.com/blog/images/2026/03/stancy-portrait.jpg" '
                         '/></p>\n'
                         '<p>Theresa is a passionate community builder serving '
                         'in the DSF Events Support Working Group. She has '
                         'demonstrated strong leadership by taking on roles '
                         'such as Local Organizer Commitee (LOC) Program Lead '
                         'at PyCon Africa 2024 and Programs Chair for PyCon '
                         'Ghana 2025. She also organized DjangoGirls events '
                         'across multiple PyCons, including PyCon Ghana 2022 '
                         'and PyCon Africa 2024.</p>\n'
                         '<p>You can learn more about Theresa by visiting <a '
                         'href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/theresa-seyram-agbenyegah/">Theresa\'s '
                         'LinkedIn profile</a> and <a '
                         'href="https://github.com/Stancy-ai/">her GitHub '
                         'Profile</a>.</p>\n'
                         '<p>Let’s spend some time getting to know Theresa '
                         'better!</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-can-you-tell-us-a-little-about-yourself-hobbies-education-etc">Can '
                         'you tell us a little about yourself (hobbies, '
                         'education, etc)?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>I’m Theresa Seyram Agbenyegah, mostly referred to '
                         'in the community as '
                         '<strong><em>Stancy</em></strong>;  a backend '
                         'engineer, social entrepreneur, and an open source '
                         'advocate/contributor passionate about using '
                         'technology for impact. My background is in '
                         'technology, community management, and systems '
                         'design. Over the years, I have grown into roles that '
                         'combine engineering, leadership, and ecosystem '
                         'building.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-i-know-many-folks-call-you-stancy-me-included-why-specifically-this-name">I '
                         'know many folks call you Stancy, me included, why '
                         'specifically this name?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>So “Stancy” is my initials 😁, People think it is '
                         'my nickname. </p>\n'
                         '<h4 id="s-how-did-you-start-using-django">How did '
                         'you start using Django?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>I was introduced to Django through a Django Girls '
                         'workshop, and <strong><em>oh i’m a Django '
                         'girl</em></strong>. I loved how opinionated yet '
                         'flexible it was. The “batteries-included” philosophy '
                         'made backend architecture feel structured without '
                         'being restrictive.</p>\n'
                         '<p>The admin interface especially blew my mind early '
                         'on; being able to scaffold powerful internal tools '
                         'so quickly felt magical.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-what-other-frameworks-do-you-know-and-if-you-had-magical-powers-what-would-you-add-to-django">What '
                         'other frameworks do you know, and if you had magical '
                         'powers, what would you add to Django?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>I have worked with Flask, FastAPI, and explored '
                         'the Dart framework. Each has strengths, especially '
                         'FastAPI in performance and modern async '
                         'patterns.</p>\n'
                         '<p>If I had magical powers, I would:</p>\n'
                         '<ul>\n'
                         '<li>Make async patterns even more seamless across '
                         'the ecosystem  </li>\n'
                         '<li>Improve first class support for large scale '
                         'distributed system  </li>\n'
                         '<li>Provide even more built-in tooling for '
                         'observability and performance profiling</li>\n'
                         '</ul>\n'
                         '<p>But overall, Django’s maturity and ecosystem are '
                         'hard to beat.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 id="s-what-projects-are-you-working-on-now">What '
                         'projects are you working on now?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>I’m not working on any big projects  at the '
                         "moment, I'm mostly working on client projects at "
                         'work.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-which-django-libraries-are-your-favorite-core-or-3rd-party">Which '
                         'Django libraries are your favorite (core or 3rd '
                         'party)?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>Some of my favorites:</p>\n'
                         '<ul>\n'
                         '<li><strong>Django Rest Framework</strong> (it’s '
                         'practically essential for modern APIs)  </li>\n'
                         '<li>django-filter  </li>\n'
                         '<li>django-allauth  </li>\n'
                         '<li>Celery (for async task processing)  </li>\n'
                         '<li>Django Debug Toolbar (for development '
                         'clarity)</li>\n'
                         '</ul>\n'
                         '<p>The ecosystem really makes Django powerful.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-what-are-the-top-three-things-in-django-that-you-like">What '
                         'are the top three things in Django that you '
                         'like?</h4>\n'
                         '<ol>\n'
                         '<li>The admin interface  </li>\n'
                         '<li>The ORM  </li>\n'
                         '<li>The strong community and documentation (FYI: it '
                         'gives me a sense of belonging)<br />\n'
                         '<strong><em>Django feels stable, mature, and '
                         'production-ready which builds developer '
                         'confidence.</em></strong></li>\n'
                         '</ol>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-you-have-been-in-the-organization-of-pycon-africa-and-djangogirls-that-happen-during-this-conference-in-2024-thats-great-do-you-have-any-advice-for-people-who-would-like-to-join-or-create-their-own-djangogirls-event-in-their-city">You '
                         'have been in the organization of PyCon Africa and '
                         'DjangoGirls that happen during this conference in '
                         "2024. That's great, do you have any advice for "
                         'people who would like to join or create their own '
                         'DjangoGirls event in their city?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>Start small and start with intention.</p>\n'
                         '<p>You don’t need a massive budget. What you need '
                         'is:</p>\n'
                         '<ul>\n'
                         '<li>A committed small team  </li>\n'
                         '<li>Clear structure  </li>\n'
                         '<li>Support from the global DjangoGirls '
                         'organization, Django Software Foundation, and other '
                         'communities.  </li>\n'
                         '<li>A safe, welcoming environment</li>\n'
                         '</ul>\n'
                         '<p>Most importantly, center the participants. The '
                         'goal isn’t just teaching Django, it’s building '
                         'confidence and introducing them to the Tech '
                         'industry.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-how-did-you-become-a-leader-of-the-pyladies-ghana-chapter">How '
                         'did you become a leader of the PyLadies Ghana '
                         'chapter?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>My Leadership journey in the PyLadies Ghana '
                         'community began with a simple step: attending a '
                         'Django Girls workshop at Ho while I was in school. '
                         'At the time, I was just curious and eager to learn '
                         'more about programming. After the workshop, I was '
                         'introduced to the PyLadies Ghana community and added '
                         'to the group. That was my first real connection to a '
                         'tech community.</p>\n'
                         '<p>I started by simply showing up, participating in '
                         'conversations, attending events, and learning from '
                         'others in the community. Over time, I became more '
                         'involved. I joined the PyLadies Ghana Tema Chapter, '
                         'where I supported the community lead with organizing '
                         'activities that are bootcamps, meetups,etc. Through '
                         'that experience, I had the opportunity to contribute '
                         'more actively.</p>\n'
                         '<p>Because of my commitment and willingness to help, '
                         'I was later asked to volunteer as a co-lead of '
                         'PyLadies Ghana Tema Chapter. I accepted the '
                         'opportunity and began working more closely with the '
                         'Lead to organize events, support members, and grow '
                         'the community. It was a period of learning, '
                         'collaboration, and service.</p>\n'
                         '<p>As I continued contributing and volunteering, '
                         'more opportunities opened up. When there was a '
                         'chance to volunteer with PyLadies Ghana programs and '
                         'events, I stepped forward again and volunteered as '
                         'PyLadies Ghana Programs and Events Lead. That '
                         'experience eventually led to me becoming a '
                         'lead.</p>\n'
                         '<p>Looking back, my journey with PyLadies Ghana has '
                         'been shaped by community, consistency, and '
                         'volunteering. What started as attending a workshop '
                         'grew into leadership and the chance to help create '
                         'opportunities for others. It reminds me that '
                         'sometimes all it takes is showing up, contributing '
                         'where you can, and being willing to grow with the '
                         'community.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-you-have-been-organizing-a-lot-of-events-in-africa-especially-in-ghana-how-do-you-envision-organizing-an-event-would-you-like-additional-support">You '
                         'have been organizing a lot of events in Africa, '
                         'especially in Ghana. How do you envision organizing '
                         'an event? Would you like additional support?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>For me, events are ecosystems, not just '
                         'gatherings.</p>\n'
                         '<p>Focus on:</p>\n'
                         '<ul>\n'
                         '<li>Clear goals and impact  </li>\n'
                         '<li>Accessibility  </li>\n'
                         '<li>Diversity of voices  </li>\n'
                         '<li>Strong logistics planning  </li>\n'
                         '<li>Follow-up community building</li>\n'
                         '</ul>\n'
                         '<p>Yes, more funding support, institutional '
                         'partnerships for internships, and long-term '
                         'sponsorship pipelines would significantly help '
                         'African tech communities scale sustainably.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-this-is-the-international-womens-day-today-im-glad-to-have-you-featured-on-this-special-day-do-you-have-any-word-to-mention-in-relation-to-this">This '
                         "is the international women's day today, I'm glad to "
                         'have you featured on this special day. Do you have '
                         'any word to mention in relation to this?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>International Women’s Day is a reminder that '
                         "representation is not a trend, it's a "
                         'necessity.</p>\n'
                         '<p>We need more women building systems, shaping '
                         'infrastructure, leading conversations, and owning '
                         'technical spaces.</p>\n'
                         '<p>And to every woman in tech: your presence is '
                         'powerful. Keep building. Keep speaking. Keep '
                         'leading. Keep mentoring and raising the next tech '
                         'women.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-what-are-your-hobbies-or-what-do-you-do-when-youre-not-working">What '
                         'are your hobbies or what do you do when you’re not '
                         'working?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>When I’m not working, I’m usually reading '
                         'books/articles, mentoring, watching movies or '
                         'documentaries, cooking,  reflecting, or exploring '
                         'new ideas around technology and social impact. I '
                         'also enjoy quiet strategy sessions with myself, '
                         'thinking about how to build things that outlive '
                         'me.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-is-there-anything-else-youd-like-to-say">Is '
                         'there anything else you’d like to say?</h4>\n'
                         "<p>Technology is more than code, it's access, power, "
                         'and possibility.</p>\n'
                         '<p>I hope more people see themselves not just as '
                         'users of technology, but as architects of it.</p>\n'
                         '<hr />\n'
                         '<p><strong>Thank you for doing the interview, Stancy '
                         '!</strong></p>',
              'summary_detail': {'base': 'https://www.djangoproject.com/rss/weblog/',
                                 'language': 'en',
                                 'type': 'text/html',
                                 'value': '<p>For March 2026, we welcome '
                                          'Theresa Seyram Agbenyegah as our '
                                          'DSF member of the month! ⭐</p>\n'
                                          '<p><img alt="Theresa portrait, a '
                                          'pretty black woman with short hair. '
                                          'She is looking at the camera with a '
                                          'big smile. She wears a white '
                                          't-shirt with written in green '
                                          '&quot;Django Girls Koforidua&quot;. '
                                          'The background is blurry but really '
                                          'colorful with shades of green and '
                                          'orange." '
                                          'src="https://media.djangoproject.com/blog/images/2026/03/stancy-portrait.jpg" '
                                          '/></p>\n'
                                          '<p>Theresa is a passionate '
                                          'community builder serving in the '
                                          'DSF Events Support Working Group. '
                                          'She has demonstrated strong '
                                          'leadership by taking on roles such '
                                          'as Local Organizer Commitee (LOC) '
                                          'Program Lead at PyCon Africa 2024 '
                                          'and Programs Chair for PyCon Ghana '
                                          '2025. She also organized '
                                          'DjangoGirls events across multiple '
                                          'PyCons, including PyCon Ghana 2022 '
                                          'and PyCon Africa 2024.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>You can learn more about Theresa '
                                          'by visiting <a '
                                          'href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/theresa-seyram-agbenyegah/">Theresa\'s '
                                          'LinkedIn profile</a> and <a '
                                          'href="https://github.com/Stancy-ai/">her '
                                          'GitHub Profile</a>.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>Let’s spend some time getting to '
                                          'know Theresa better!</p>\n'
