                         'type': 'text/html'}],
              'published': 'Tue, 24 Feb 2026 15:58:24 -0600',
              'published_parsed': time.struct_time(tm_year=2026, tm_mon=2, tm_mday=24, tm_hour=21, tm_min=58, tm_sec=24, tm_wday=1, tm_yday=55, tm_isdst=0),
              'summary': '<p>When we learned that the Django Software '
                         'Foundation has been accepted as a mentoring '
                         'organization for Google Summer of Code 2026, it '
                         'marked another steady milestone in a long-standing '
                         'relationship. Django first participated in GSoC in '
                         '2006, and 2026 represents our 21st consecutive year '
                         'in the program. </p>\n'
                         '<p>Over two decades, GSoC has become a consistent '
                         'pathway for contributors to engage more deeply with '
                         'Django — not just through a summer project, but '
                         'often through continued involvement that extends '
                         'well beyond the official coding period.</p>\n'
                         '<p>For many of you reading this, this might be your '
                         'first exposure to how Django’s open source ecosystem '
                         'works. So before we get into applications and '
                         'expectations, let’s take a step back and understand '
                         'the environment you’re stepping into.</p>\n'
                         '<h3 '
                         'id="s-understanding-the-django-ecosystem">Understanding '
                         'the Django Ecosystem</h3>\n'
                         '<p>The Django Software Foundation (DSF) is the '
                         'non-profit organization that supports the long-term '
                         'sustainability of Django. Django itself is developed '
                         'entirely in the open. Feature discussions, '
                         'architectural debates, bug reports, design '
                         'proposals, and code reviews all happen '
                         'publicly.</p>\n'
                         '<p>That openness is intentional. It allows anyone, '
                         'from anywhere in the world, to participate. But it '
                         'also means decisions are rarely made quickly or '
                         'casually. Changes are discussed carefully. '
                         'Trade-offs are evaluated. Backwards compatibility is '
                         'taken seriously.</p>\n'
                         '<p>If you are new, it helps to understand the main '
                         'spaces where this work happens:</p>\n'
                         '<ul>\n'
                         '<li>The <a '
                         'href="https://forum.djangoproject.com/">Django '
                         'Forum</a> is where broader discussions take place — '
                         'new feature ideas, design direction, and community '
                         'conversations.  </li>\n'
                         '<li><a '
                         'href="https://code.djangoproject.com/query">Django '
                         'Trac</a> is the issue tracker, where bugs, feature '
                         'requests, and patches are formally recorded and '
                         'reviewed. If no one is working on an issue, you can '
                         'assign it yourself and start working on it.  </li>\n'
                         '<li>Code contributions happen through <a '
                         'href="https://github.com/django/django">pull '
                         'requests</a>, where proposed changes are reviewed, '
                         'tested, and discussed in detail before being '
                         'merged.  </li>\n'
                         '<li>New features are proposed and discussed in the '
                         '<a '
                         'href="https://github.com/django/new-features/">new-features '
                         'repository</a>. There is a <a '
                         'href="https://github.com/orgs/django/projects/24">project '
                         'board view</a> that shows the state of each '
                         'proposal.</li>\n'
                         '</ul>\n'
                         '<p>For someone new, this ecosystem can feel '
                         'overwhelming at first. Threads may reference '
                         'decisions made years ago. Review comments can be '
                         'detailed. Standards are high.</p>\n'
                         '<p>That is precisely why GSoC matters to us. It '
                         'provides a structured entry point into this culture, '
                         'with mentorship and guidance along the way, helping '
                         'contributors understand not just how to write code — '
                         'but how Django evolves.</p>\n'
                         '<h3 id="s-why-the-django-forum-is-central">Why the '
                         'Django Forum Is Central</h3>\n'
                         '<p>Most GSoC journeys in Django begin on the <a '
                         'href="https://forum.djangoproject.com/c/internals/mentorship/10">Django '
                         'Forum</a> — the community’s public space for '
                         'technical discussions about features, design '
                         'decisions, and improvements to Django.</p>\n'
                         '<p>Introducing yourself there is not a formality; it '
                         'is often your first real contribution. When you '
                         'discuss a project idea publicly, you demonstrate how '
                         'you think, how you respond to feedback, and how you '
                         'handle technical trade-offs. Questions and '
                         'challenges from mentors are not barriers — they are '
                         'part of the collaborative design process.</p>\n'
                         '<p>Proposals that grow through open discussion on '
                         'the Forum are almost always stronger than those '
                         'written in isolation.</p>\n'
                         '<h3 id="s-what-to-do">What To Do</h3>\n'
                         '<p>If you are planning to apply for GSoC 2026 with '
                         'Django, here is what we strongly encourage:</p>\n'
                         '<p><strong>Start early.</strong><br />\n'
                         'Do not wait until the application window opens. '
                         'Begin discussions well in advance.</p>\n'
                         '<p><strong>Engage publicly.</strong><br />\n'
                         'Introduce yourself on the <a '
                         'href="https://forum.djangoproject.com/c/internals/mentorship/10">Forum</a>. '
                         'Participate in ongoing threads. Show consistent '
                         'involvement rather than one-time activity.</p>\n'
                         '<p><strong>Demonstrate understanding(very '
                         'important)</strong><br />\n'
                         'Read related tickets and past discussions. Reference '
                         'them in your proposal. Show that you understand the '
                         'technical and philosophical context.</p>\n'
                         '<p><strong>Be realistic about scope.</strong><br />\n'
                         'Ambitious ideas are welcome, but they must be '
                         'grounded in technical feasibility within the GSoC '
                         'timeframe.</p>\n'
                         '<p><strong>Show iteration.</strong><br />\n'
                         'If your proposal evolves because of feedback, that '
                         'is a positive signal. It shows adaptability and '
                         'thoughtful engagement.</p>\n'
                         '<p><strong>What Not To Do</strong></p>\n'
                         '<p>Equally important are the expectations around '
                         'what we will not consider.</p>\n'
                         '<p><strong>Do not submit a proposal without prior '
                         'discussion.</strong><br />\n'
                         'A proposal that appears for the first time in the '
                         'application form, without any Forum engagement, will '
                         'be at a disadvantage.</p>\n'
                         '<p><strong>Do not generate a proposal using AI and '
                         'submit it as-is.</strong><br />\n'
                         'If a proposal is clearly AI-generated, lacks '
                         'discussion history, and shows no evidence of '
                         'personal understanding, it will be rejected. We '
                         'evaluate your reasoning process, not just the '
                         'surface quality of the document.</p>\n'
                         '<p><strong>Do not copy previous '
                         'proposals.</strong><br />\n'
                         'Each year’s context is different. We expect original '
                         'thinking and up-to-date understanding.</p>\n'
                         '<p><strong>Do not treat GSoC as a solo '
                         'internship.</strong><br />\n'
                         'Django development is collaborative. If you are '
                         'uncomfortable discussing ideas publicly or receiving '
                         'detailed feedback, this may not be the right '
                         'fit.</p>\n'
                         '<p><strong>Do not submit empty or placeholder '
                         'proposal documents.</strong><br />\n'
                         'In previous years, we have received blank or '
                         'near-empty submissions, which create unnecessary '
                         'effort for volunteer reviewers. Such proposals will '
                         'not be considered.</p>\n'
                         '<p><strong>Do not repeatedly tag or ping maintainers '
                         'for reviews.</strong><br />\n'
                         'Once you’ve submitted your proposal or patch, give '
                         'reviewers time to respond. Maintainers are '
                         'volunteers managing many responsibilities, and '
                         'repeated tagging does not speed up the process. '
                         'Patience and respectful follow-ups (after a '
                         'reasonable interval) are appreciated.</p>\n'
                         '<h3 id="s-on-ai-usage">On AI Usage</h3>\n'
                         '<p>We recognize that AI tools are now part of many '
                         'developers’ workflows. Using AI to explore '
                         'documentation, clarify syntax, or organize thoughts '
                         'is not inherently a problem.</p>\n'
                         '<p>However, AI must not replace ownership.</p>\n'
                         '<p>You should be able to clearly explain your '
                         'architectural decisions, justify trade-offs, and '
                         'respond thoughtfully when challenged. If you cannot '
                         'defend your own proposal without external '
                         'assistance, it signals a lack of readiness for this '
                         'kind of work.</p>\n'
                         '<p>The quality we look for is not perfect language — '
                         'it is depth of understanding.</p>\n'
                         '<h3 '
                         'id="s-im-a-first-time-contributor-to-django-what-should-i-do">I’m '
                         'a First-Time Contributor to Django — What Should I '
                         'Do?</h3>\n'
                         '<p>If this is your first time contributing to '
                         'Django, start simple and start early.</p>\n'
                         '<p>First, spend some time understanding how Django '
                         'works as an open source project. Read a few recent '
                         'discussions on the <a '
                         'href="https://forum.djangoproject.com">Django '
                         'Forum</a> and browse <a '
                         'href="https://code.djangoproject.com/query">open '
                         'tickets</a> to see the kinds of problems being '
                         'discussed.</p>\n'
                         '<p>Next, introduce yourself on the Forum. Share your '
                         'background briefly and mention what areas interest '
                         'you. You don’t need to have a perfect project idea '
                         'on day one — curiosity and willingness to learn '
                         'matter more.</p>\n'
                         '<p>Then:</p>\n'
                         '<ul>\n'
                         '<li>Read the official <a '
                         'href="https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/stable/internals/contributing/new-contributors/">first '
                         'time contributor guide</a> carefully.   </li>\n'
                         '<li>Try setting up Django locally and run the test '
                         'suite.  </li>\n'
                         '<li>Look for small tickets on <a '
                         'href="https://code.djangoproject.com/query">trac</a> '
                         '(including documentation or cleanup tasks) to '
                         'understand the workflow.  </li>\n'
                         '<li>Ask questions on the <a '
                         'href="https://forum.djangoproject.com">Forum</a> or '
                         'in <a '
                         'href="https://chat.djangoproject.com">Discord</a> if '
                         'something is unclear.</li>\n'
                         '</ul>\n'
                         '<p>Most importantly, be patient with yourself. '
                         'Django is a mature and widely used framework, and it '
                         'takes time to understand its design principles and '
                         'contribution standards.</p>\n'
                         '<p>Strong contributors are not the ones who know '
                         'everything at the start — they are the ones who show '
                         'up consistently, engage thoughtfully, and improve '
                         'through feedback.</p>\n'
                         '<h3 id="s-to-conclude">To conclude</h3>\n'
                         '<p>We are excited to welcome a new group of '
                         'contributors into the Django ecosystem through '
                         'Google Summer of Code 2026. We look forward to '
                         'thoughtful ideas, constructive discussions, and a '
                         'summer of meaningful collaboration — built not just '
                         'on code, but on understanding and shared '
                         'responsibility.</p>',
              'summary_detail': {'base': 'https://www.djangoproject.com/rss/weblog/',
                                 'language': 'en',
                                 'type': 'text/html',
                                 'value': '<p>When we learned that the Django '
                                          'Software Foundation has been '
                                          'accepted as a mentoring '
                                          'organization for Google Summer of '
                                          'Code 2026, it marked another steady '
                                          'milestone in a long-standing '
                                          'relationship. Django first '
                                          'participated in GSoC in 2006, and '
                                          '2026 represents our 21st '
                                          'consecutive year in the program. '
                                          '</p>\n'
                                          '<p>Over two decades, GSoC has '
                                          'become a consistent pathway for '
                                          'contributors to engage more deeply '
                                          'with Django — not just through a '
                                          'summer project, but often through '
                                          'continued involvement that extends '
                                          'well beyond the official coding '
                                          'period.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>For many of you reading this, '
                                          'this might be your first exposure '
                                          'to how Django’s open source '
                                          'ecosystem works. So before we get '
                                          'into applications and expectations, '
                                          'let’s take a step back and '
                                          'understand the environment you’re '
                                          'stepping into.</p>\n'
                                          '<h3 '
                                          'id="s-understanding-the-django-ecosystem">Understanding '
                                          'the Django Ecosystem</h3>\n'
                                          '<p>The Django Software Foundation '
                                          '(DSF) is the non-profit '
                                          'organization that supports the '
                                          'long-term sustainability of Django. '
                                          'Django itself is developed entirely '
                                          'in the open. Feature discussions, '
                                          'architectural debates, bug reports, '
                                          'design proposals, and code reviews '
                                          'all happen publicly.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>That openness is intentional. It '
                                          'allows anyone, from anywhere in the '
                                          'world, to participate. But it also '
                                          'means decisions are rarely made '
                                          'quickly or casually. Changes are '
                                          'discussed carefully. Trade-offs are '
                                          'evaluated. Backwards compatibility '
                                          'is taken seriously.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>If you are new, it helps to '
                                          'understand the main spaces where '
                                          'this work happens:</p>\n'
                                          '<ul>\n'
                                          '<li>The <a '
                                          'href="https://forum.djangoproject.com/">Django '
                                          'Forum</a> is where broader '
                                          'discussions take place — new '
                                          'feature ideas, design direction, '
                                          'and community conversations.  '
                                          '</li>\n'
                                          '<li><a '
                                          'href="https://code.djangoproject.com/query">Django '
                                          'Trac</a> is the issue tracker, '
                                          'where bugs, feature requests, and '
                                          'patches are formally recorded and '
                                          'reviewed. If no one is working on '
                                          'an issue, you can assign it '
                                          'yourself and start working on it.  '
                                          '</li>\n'
                                          '<li>Code contributions happen '
                                          'through <a '
                                          'href="https://github.com/django/django">pull '
                                          'requests</a>, where proposed '
                                          'changes are reviewed, tested, and '
                                          'discussed in detail before being '
                                          'merged.  </li>\n'
                                          '<li>New features are proposed and '
                                          'discussed in the <a '
                                          'href="https://github.com/django/new-features/">new-features '
                                          'repository</a>. There is a <a '
                                          'href="https://github.com/orgs/django/projects/24">project '
                                          'board view</a> that shows the state '
                                          'of each proposal.</li>\n'
                                          '</ul>\n'
                                          '<p>For someone new, this ecosystem '
                                          'can feel overwhelming at first. '
                                          'Threads may reference decisions '
                                          'made years ago. Review comments can '
                                          'be detailed. Standards are '
                                          'high.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>That is precisely why GSoC '
                                          'matters to us. It provides a '
                                          'structured entry point into this '
                                          'culture, with mentorship and '
                                          'guidance along the way, helping '
                                          'contributors understand not just '
                                          'how to write code — but how Django '
                                          'evolves.</p>\n'
                                          '<h3 '
                                          'id="s-why-the-django-forum-is-central">Why '
                                          'the Django Forum Is Central</h3>\n'
