              'published': 'Wed, 21 Jan 2026 12:13:15 -0600',
              'published_parsed': time.struct_time(tm_year=2026, tm_mon=1, tm_mday=21, tm_hour=18, tm_min=13, tm_sec=15, tm_wday=2, tm_yday=21, tm_isdst=0),
              'summary': '<p>We are thrilled to announce that Djangonaut '
                         'Space, a mentorship program for contributing to '
                         'Django, is <a '
                         'href="https://djangonaut.space/sessions/2026-session-6/">open '
                         'for applicants for our next cohort!</a> 🚀</p>\n'
                         '<p>Djangonaut Space is holding a sixth session! This '
                         'session will start on March 2nd, 2026. We are '
                         'currently accepting applications until '
                         '<strong>February 2nd, 2026 Anywhere on '
                         'Earth</strong>. More details can be found in the <a '
                         'href="https://djangonaut.space/comms/2026/01/18/2026-opening-session-6/">website</a>.</p>\n'
                         '<p>Djangonaut Space is a free, 8-week group '
                         'mentoring program where individuals will work '
                         'self-paced in a semi-structured learning '
                         'environment. It seeks to help members of the '
                         'community who wish to level up their current Django '
                         'code contributions and potentially take on '
                         'leadership roles in Django in the future.</p>\n'
                         '<blockquote>\n'
                         "<p>“I'm so grateful to have been a part of the "
                         "Djangonaut Space program. It's a wonderfully warm, "
                         'diverse, and welcoming space, and the perfect place '
                         'to get started with Django contributions. The '
                         'community is full of bright, talented individuals '
                         'who are making time to help and guide others, which '
                         'is truly a joy to experience. Before Djangonaut '
                         "Space, I felt as though I wasn't the kind of person "
                         'who could become a Django contributor; now I feel '
                         'like I found a place where I belong.” - Eliana, '
                         'Djangonaut Session 1</p>\n'
                         '</blockquote>\n'
                         '<p>Enthusiastic about contributing to Django but '
                         'wondering what we have in store for you? No worries, '
                         'we have got you covered! 🤝</p>\n'
                         '<p>✏️ <a '
                         'href="https://djangonaut.space/comms/2026/01/18/2026-opening-session-6/">Mission '
                         'Briefing</a></p>\n'
                         '<p>📷 <a href="https://youtu.be/6bjCIOCpdM4">AMA '
                         'Recap</a></p>',
              'summary_detail': {'base': 'https://www.djangoproject.com/rss/weblog/',
                                 'language': 'en',
                                 'type': 'text/html',
                                 'value': '<p>We are thrilled to announce that '
                                          'Djangonaut Space, a mentorship '
                                          'program for contributing to Django, '
                                          'is <a '
                                          'href="https://djangonaut.space/sessions/2026-session-6/">open '
                                          'for applicants for our next '
                                          'cohort!</a> 🚀</p>\n'
                                          '<p>Djangonaut Space is holding a '
                                          'sixth session! This session will '
                                          'start on March 2nd, 2026. We are '
                                          'currently accepting applications '
                                          'until <strong>February 2nd, 2026 '
                                          'Anywhere on Earth</strong>. More '
                                          'details can be found in the <a '
                                          'href="https://djangonaut.space/comms/2026/01/18/2026-opening-session-6/">website</a>.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>Djangonaut Space is a free, '
                                          '8-week group mentoring program '
                                          'where individuals will work '
                                          'self-paced in a semi-structured '
                                          'learning environment. It seeks to '
                                          'help members of the community who '
                                          'wish to level up their current '
                                          'Django code contributions and '
                                          'potentially take on leadership '
                                          'roles in Django in the future.</p>\n'
                                          '<blockquote>\n'
                                          "<p>“I'm so grateful to have been a "
                                          'part of the Djangonaut Space '
                                          "program. It's a wonderfully warm, "
                                          'diverse, and welcoming space, and '
                                          'the perfect place to get started '
                                          'with Django contributions. The '
                                          'community is full of bright, '
                                          'talented individuals who are making '
                                          'time to help and guide others, '
                                          'which is truly a joy to experience. '
                                          'Before Djangonaut Space, I felt as '
                                          "though I wasn't the kind of person "
                                          'who could become a Django '
                                          'contributor; now I feel like I '
                                          'found a place where I belong.” - '
                                          'Eliana, Djangonaut Session 1</p>\n'
                                          '</blockquote>\n'
                                          '<p>Enthusiastic about contributing '
                                          'to Django but wondering what we '
                                          'have in store for you? No worries, '
                                          'we have got you covered! 🤝</p>\n'
                                          '<p>✏️ <a '
                                          'href="https://djangonaut.space/comms/2026/01/18/2026-opening-session-6/">Mission '
                                          'Briefing</a></p>\n'
                                          '<p>📷 <a '
                                          'href="https://youtu.be/6bjCIOCpdM4">AMA '
                                          'Recap</a></p>'},
              'title': 'Djangonaut Space - Session 6 Accepting Applications',
              'title_detail': {'base': 'https://www.djangoproject.com/rss/weblog/',
                               'language': 'en',
                               'type': 'text/plain',
                               'value': 'Djangonaut Space - Session 6 '
                                        'Accepting Applications'}},
             {'author': 'Sarah Abderemane',
              'author_detail': {'name': 'Sarah Abderemane'},
              'authors': [{'name': 'Sarah Abderemane'}],
              'guidislink': False,
              'id': 'https://www.djangoproject.com/weblog/2026/jan/15/dsf-member-of-the-month-omar-abou-mrad/',
              'link': 'https://www.djangoproject.com/weblog/2026/jan/15/dsf-member-of-the-month-omar-abou-mrad/',
              'links': [{'href': 'https://www.djangoproject.com/weblog/2026/jan/15/dsf-member-of-the-month-omar-abou-mrad/',
                         'rel': 'alternate',
                         'type': 'text/html'}],
              'published': 'Thu, 15 Jan 2026 08:14:37 -0600',
              'published_parsed': time.struct_time(tm_year=2026, tm_mon=1, tm_mday=15, tm_hour=14, tm_min=14, tm_sec=37, tm_wday=3, tm_yday=15, tm_isdst=0),
              'summary': '<p>For January 2026, we welcome Omar Abou Mrad as '
                         'our DSF member of the month! ⭐</p>\n'
                         '<p><img alt="Omar sitting on a couch" '
                         'src="https://media.djangoproject.com/blog/images/2026/01/omar_QutqeAO.jpg" '
                         '/></p>\n'
                         '<p>Omar is a helper in the Django Discord server, he '
                         'has helped and continuously help folks around the '
                         'world in their Django journey! He is part of the '
                         'Discord Staff Team. He has been a DSF member since '
                         'June 2024.   </p>\n'
                         '<p>You can learn more about Omar by visiting <a '
                         'href="https://xterm.info/">Omar\'s website</a> and '
                         '<a href="https://github.com/omaraboumrad">his GitHub '
                         'Profile</a>.</p>\n'
                         '<p>Let’s spend some time getting to know Omar '
                         'better!</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-can-you-tell-us-a-little-about-yourself-hobbies-education-etc">Can '
                         'you tell us a little about yourself? (hobbies, '
                         'education, etc)</h4>\n'
                         '<p>Hello! My name is Omar Abou Mrad, a 47-year-old '
                         'husband to a beautiful wife and father of three '
                         'teenage boys. I’m from Lebanon (Middle East), have a '
                         'Computer Science background, and currently work as a '
                         'Technical Lead on a day-to-day basis. I’m mostly '
                         'high on life and quite enthusiastic about '
                         'technology, sports, food, and much more!</p>\n'
                         '<p>I love learning new things and I love helping '
                         'people. Most of my friends, acquaintances, and '
                         'generally people online know me as Xterm.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-i-have-already-an-idea-but-where-your-nickname-xterm-comes-from">I '
                         'have already an idea but where your nickname "Xterm" '
                         'comes from?</h4>\n'
                         '<p><strong>xterm</strong> is simply <a '
                         'href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xterm">the '
                         'terminal emulator for the X Window System</a>. I '
                         'first encountered it back in the mid to late 90s '
                         'when I started using Redhat 2.0 operating system. '
                         'Things weren’t easy to set up back then, and the '
                         'terminal was where you spent most of your time.</p>\n'
                         '<p>Nevertheless, I had to wait months (or was it '
                         'years?) on end for the nickname "Xterm" to expire on '
                         '<a '
                         'href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freenode">Freenode</a> '
                         'back in mid 2000s, before I snatched and registered '
                         'it.</p>\n'
                         "<p>Alas, I did! Xterm, c'est moi! &gt;:-]</p>\n"
                         '<h4 id="s-how-did-you-start-using-django">How did '
                         'you start using Django?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>We landed on Django (~1.1) fairly early at work, '
                         'as we wanted to use Python with an ORM while '
                         'building websites for different clients. The real '
                         'challenge came when we took on a project responsible '
                         'for managing operations, traceability, and reporting '
                         'at a pipe-manufacturing company.</p>\n'
                         '<p>By that time, most of the team was already '
                         'well-versed in Django (~1.6), and we went head-on '
                         'into building one of the most complicated '
                         'applications we had done to date, everything from '
                         'the back office to operators’ devices connected to a '
                         'Django-powered system.</p>\n'
                         '<p>Since then, most of our projects have been built '
                         'with Django at the core.</p>\n'
                         '<p>We love Django.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-what-other-framework-do-you-know-and-if-there-is-anything-you-would-like-to-have-in-django-if-you-had-magical-powers">What '
                         'other framework do you know and if there is anything '
                         'you would like to have in Django if you had magical '
                         'powers?</h4>\n'
                         "<p>I've used a multitude of frameworks "
                         'professionally before Django, primarily in Java (EE, '
                         'SeamFramework, ...) and .NET (ASP.NET, ASP.NET MVC) '
                         'as well as sampling different frameworks for '
                         'educational purposes.</p>\n'
                         '<p>I suppose if I could snap my fingers and get '
                         "things to exist in django it wouldn't be something "
                         '<em>new</em> as much as it is official support '
                         'of:</p>\n'
                         '<ul>\n'
                         '<li>Built-in and opinionated way to deal with '
                         'hierarchical data in the ORM alongside the '
                         'supporting API for building and traversing them '
                         'optimally.</li>\n'
                         '<li>Built-in websockets support. Essentially the <a '
                         'href="https://channels.readthedocs.io/en/latest/">django-channel</a> '
                         'experience.</li>\n'
                         '<li>Built-in ORM support for common constructs like '
                         'CTEs, and possibly the ability to transition from '
                         'raw SQL into a queryset pipeline.</li>\n'
                         '</ul>\n'
                         "<p>But since we're finger-snapping things to "
                         'existence, it would be awesome if every component of '
                         'django (core, orm, templates, forms, "all") could be '
                         'installed separately in such a way that you could '
                         'cherry pick what you want to install, so we could '
                         'dismiss those pesky (cough) '
                         '<strong>arguments</strong> (cough) about Django '
                         'being <em>bulky</em>.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 id="s-what-projects-are-you-working-on-now">What '
                         'projects are you working on now?</h4>\n'
                         "<p>I'm involved in numerous projects currently at "
                         'work, most of which are based on Django, but the one '
                         "I'm working right now consists of doing integrations "
                         'and synchronizations with <a '
                         'href="https://www.sap.com/products/data-cloud/hana/what-is-sap-hana.html">SAP '
                         'HANA</a> for different modules, in different '
                         'applications.</p>\n'
                         "<p>It's quite the challenge, which makes it twice "
                         'the fun.</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-which-django-libraries-are-your-favorite-core-or-3rd-party">Which '
                         'Django libraries are your favorite (core or 3rd '
                         'party)?</h4>\n'
                         '<ul>\n'
                         '<li><a '
                         'href="https://django-debug-toolbar.readthedocs.io/en/latest/">django-debug-toolbar</a> '
                         'hands down. It is an absolute beast of a library and '
                         'a required tool. It is also the lib that influenced '
                         '<a '
                         'href="https://dryorm.xterm.info/">DryORM</a></li>\n'
                         '<li><a '
                         'href="https://django-extensions.readthedocs.io/en/latest/">django-extensions</a> '
                         'obviously, for its numerous helper commands (<a '
                         'href="https://django-extensions.readthedocs.io/en/latest/shell_plus.html#sql-queries">shell_plus '
                         '--print-sql</a>, <a '
                         'href="https://django-extensions.readthedocs.io/en/latest/runserver_plus.html">runserver_plus</a>... '
                         'and much more!)</li>\n'
                         '<li><a '
                         'href="https://django-mptt.readthedocs.io/en/latest/">django-mptt</a> '
                         'while unmaintained, it remains one of my personal '
                         "favorites for hierarchical data. It's a true piece "
                         'of art.</li>\n'
                         '</ul>\n'
                         "<p>I would like to mention that I'm extremely "
                         'thankful for any and all core and 3rd Party '
                         'libraries out there!</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-what-are-the-top-three-things-in-django-that-you-like">What '
                         'are the top three things in Django that you '
                         'like?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>In no particular order:</p>\n'
                         '<ul>\n'
                         '<li>The ORM; We love it, it fits nicely with the '
                         'rest of the components.</li>\n'
                         '<li>I feel we should not dismiss what sets Django '
                         'apart from most frameworks; Its defaults, the '
                         'conventions, and how opinionated it is; If you avoid '
                         '<em>overriding</em> the defaults that you get, '
                         "you'll end up with a codebase that anyone can read, "
                         'understand and maintain easily. (This is quite '
                         'subjective and some may very well disagree! '
                         '^.^)</li>\n'
                         '<li>The documentation. Django’s documentation is '
                         'among the best out there: comprehensive, exhaustive, '
                         'and incredibly well written.</li>\n'
                         '</ul>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-you-are-helping-a-lot-of-folks-in-django-discord-what-do-you-think-is-needed-to-be-a-good-helper-according-to-you">You '
                         'are helping a lot of folks in Django Discord, what '
                         'do you think is needed to be a good helper according '
                         'to you?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>First and foremost, I want to highlight what an '
                         'excellent staff team we have on the <a '
                         'href="https://chat.djangoproject.com/">Official '
                         'Django Discord</a>. While I don’t feel I hold a '
                         'candle to what the rest of the team does daily, we '
                         'complement each other very well.</p>\n'
                         '<p>To me, being a good helper means:</p>\n'
                         '<ul>\n'
                         '<li>Having patience. You’ve built skills over many '
                         'years, and not everyone is at the same stage. People '
                         'will ask unreasonable or incorrect questions, and '
                         'sometimes they simply won’t listen.</li>\n'
                         '<li>Guiding people toward figuring things out '
                         'themselves. Giving a direct solution rarely helps in '
                         'the long run. There are no scoreboards when it comes '
                         'to helping others.</li>\n'
                         '<li>Teaching how to break problems down and reduce '
                         'noise, especially how to produce the <a '
                         'href="https://sscce.org/">bare minimum code needed '
                         'to reproduce an issue.</a></li>\n'
                         '<li>Point them to <a '
                         'href="https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/6.0/">the '
                         'official documentation</a> first, and teaching them '
                         'how to find answers.</li>\n'
                         '<li>Staying humble. No one knows everything, and you '
                         'can always learn from your peers.</li>\n'
                         '</ul>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-dry-orm-is-really-appreciated-what-motivated-you-to-create-the-project">Dry '
                         'ORM is really appreciated! What motivated you to '
                         'create the project?</h4>\n'
                         "<p>Imagine you're having a discussion with a "
                         'djangonaut friend or colleague about some data '
                         'modeling, or answering some question or concern they '
                         'have, or reviewing some ORM code in a repository on '
                         'github, or helping someone on IRC, Slack, Discord, '
                         'the forums... or simply you want to do some quick '
                         'ORM experiment but not disturb your current project. '
                         '</p>\n'
                         '<p>The most common ways people deal with this, is by '
                         'having a throw-away project that they add models to, '
                         'generate migrations, open the shell, run the queries '
                         'they want, reset the db if needed, copy the models '
                         'and the shell code into some code sharing site, then '
                         'send the link to the recipient. Not to mention '
                         'needing to store the code they experiment with in '
                         'either separate scripts or management commands so '
                         'they can have them as references for later.</p>\n'
                         '<p>I loved what DDT gave me with the queries '
                         'transparency, I loved experimenting in the shell '
                         'with <code>shell_plus --print-sql</code> and I '
                         'needed to share things online. All of this was '
                         'cumbersome and that’s when DryORM came into '
                         'existence, simplifying the entire process into a '
                         'single code snippet.</p>\n'
                         '<p>The need grew massively when I became a helper on '
                         'Official Django Discord and noticed we (Staff) could '
                         'greatly benefit from having this tool not only to '
                         'assist others, but share knowledge among ourselves. '
                         'While I never truly wanted to go <em>public</em> '
                         'with it, I was encouraged by my peers on Discord to '
                         "share it and since then, they've been extremely "
                         'supportive and assisted in its evolution.</p>\n'
                         '<p>The unexpected thing however, was for DryORM to '
                         'be used in the <a '
                         'href="https://code.djangoproject.com/timeline?from=2025-07-18T09%3A17%3A02-05%3A00&amp;precision=second">official '
                         'code tracker</a>, or the <a '
                         'href="https://forum.djangoproject.com/t/foreignkey-to-field-doesnt-require-null-false">forums</a>, '
                         'or even in <a '
                         'href="https://github.com/django/django/pull/20085#discussion_r2522802667">Github '
                         "PRs</a>! Ever since, I've decided to put a lot of "
                         'focus and effort on having features that can support '
                         'the django contributors in their quest evolve '
                         'Django.</p>\n'
                         "<p>So here's a shout-out to everyone that use "
                         'DryORM!</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-i-believe-you-are-the-main-maintainer-do-you-need-help-on-something">I '
                         'believe you are the main maintainer, do you need '
                         'help on something?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>Yes, I am and thank you! I think the application '
                         'has reached a point where new feature releases will '
                         'slow down, so it’s entering more of a maintenance '
                         'phase now, which I can manage.</p>\n'
                         "<p>Hopefully soon we'll have the discord bot "
                         'executing ORM snippet :-]</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-what-are-your-hobbies-or-what-do-you-do-when-youre-not-working">What '
                         'are your hobbies or what do you do when you’re not '
                         'working?</h4>\n'
                         "<p>Oh wow, not working, what's that like! :-]</p>\n"
                         '<p>Early mornings are usually reserved for weight '
                         'training.\\\n'
                         'Followed by a long, full workday.\\\n'
                         'Then escorting and watching the kids at practice.\\\n'
                         'Evenings are spent with my wife.\\\n'
                         'Late nights are either light gaming or some '
                         'tech-related reading and prototyping.\\</p>\n'
                         '<p>Weekends look very similar, just with many more '
                         'kids sports matches!</p>\n'
                         '<h4 '
                         'id="s-is-there-anything-else-youd-like-to-say">Is '
                         'there anything else you’d like to say?</h4>\n'
                         '<p>I want to thank everyone who helped make Django '
                         'what it is today.</p>\n'
                         '<p>If you’re reading this and aren’t yet part of the '
                         'Discord community, <a '
                         'href="https://chat.djangoproject.com/">I invite you '
                         'to join us</a>! You’ll find many like-minded people '
                         'to discuss your interests with. Whether you’re there '
                         'to help, get help, or just hang around, it’s a fun '
                         'place to be.</p>\n'
                         '<hr />\n'
                         '<p><strong>Thank you for doing the interview, '
                         'Omar!</strong></p>',
              'summary_detail': {'base': 'https://www.djangoproject.com/rss/weblog/',
                                 'language': 'en',
                                 'type': 'text/html',
                                 'value': '<p>For January 2026, we welcome '
                                          'Omar Abou Mrad as our DSF member of '
                                          'the month! ⭐</p>\n'
                                          '<p><img alt="Omar sitting on a '
                                          'couch" '
                                          'src="https://media.djangoproject.com/blog/images/2026/01/omar_QutqeAO.jpg" '
                                          '/></p>\n'
                                          '<p>Omar is a helper in the Django '
                                          'Discord server, he has helped and '
                                          'continuously help folks around the '
                                          'world in their Django journey! He '
                                          'is part of the Discord Staff Team. '
                                          'He has been a DSF member since June '
                                          '2024.   </p>\n'
                                          '<p>You can learn more about Omar by '
                                          'visiting <a '
                                          'href="https://xterm.info/">Omar\'s '
                                          'website</a> and <a '
                                          'href="https://github.com/omaraboumrad">his '
                                          'GitHub Profile</a>.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>Let’s spend some time getting to '
                                          'know Omar better!</p>\n'
                                          '<h4 '
                                          'id="s-can-you-tell-us-a-little-about-yourself-hobbies-education-etc">Can '
                                          'you tell us a little about '
                                          'yourself? (hobbies, education, '
                                          'etc)</h4>\n'
                                          '<p>Hello! My name is Omar Abou '
                                          'Mrad, a 47-year-old husband to a '
                                          'beautiful wife and father of three '
                                          'teenage boys. I’m from Lebanon '
                                          '(Middle East), have a Computer '
                                          'Science background, and currently '
                                          'work as a Technical Lead on a '
                                          'day-to-day basis. I’m mostly high '
                                          'on life and quite enthusiastic '
                                          'about technology, sports, food, and '
                                          'much more!</p>\n'
                                          '<p>I love learning new things and I '
                                          'love helping people. Most of my '
                                          'friends, acquaintances, and '
                                          'generally people online know me as '
                                          'Xterm.</p>\n'
                                          '<h4 '
                                          'id="s-i-have-already-an-idea-but-where-your-nickname-xterm-comes-from">I '
                                          'have already an idea but where your '
                                          'nickname "Xterm" comes from?</h4>\n'
                                          '<p><strong>xterm</strong> is simply '
                                          '<a '
                                          'href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xterm">the '
                                          'terminal emulator for the X Window '
                                          'System</a>. I first encountered it '
                                          'back in the mid to late 90s when I '
                                          'started using Redhat 2.0 operating '
                                          'system. Things weren’t easy to set '
                                          'up back then, and the terminal was '
                                          'where you spent most of your '
                                          'time.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>Nevertheless, I had to wait '
                                          'months (or was it years?) on end '
                                          'for the nickname "Xterm" to expire '
                                          'on <a '
                                          'href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freenode">Freenode</a> '
                                          'back in mid 2000s, before I '
                                          'snatched and registered it.</p>\n'
                                          "<p>Alas, I did! Xterm, c'est moi! "
                                          '&gt;:-]</p>\n'
                                          '<h4 '
                                          'id="s-how-did-you-start-using-django">How '
                                          'did you start using Django?</h4>\n'
                                          '<p>We landed on Django (~1.1) '
                                          'fairly early at work, as we wanted '
                                          'to use Python with an ORM while '
                                          'building websites for different '
                                          'clients. The real challenge came '
                                          'when we took on a project '
                                          'responsible for managing '
                                          'operations, traceability, and '
                                          'reporting at a pipe-manufacturing '
                                          'company.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>By that time, most of the team '
                                          'was already well-versed in Django '
                                          '(~1.6), and we went head-on into '
                                          'building one of the most '
                                          'complicated applications we had '
                                          'done to date, everything from the '
                                          'back office to operators’ devices '
                                          'connected to a Django-powered '
                                          'system.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>Since then, most of our projects '
                                          'have been built with Django at the '
                                          'core.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>We love Django.</p>\n'
                                          '<h4 '
                                          'id="s-what-other-framework-do-you-know-and-if-there-is-anything-you-would-like-to-have-in-django-if-you-had-magical-powers">What '
                                          'other framework do you know and if '
                                          'there is anything you would like to '
                                          'have in Django if you had magical '
                                          'powers?</h4>\n'
                                          "<p>I've used a multitude of "
                                          'frameworks professionally before '
                                          'Django, primarily in Java (EE, '
                                          'SeamFramework, ...) and .NET '
                                          '(ASP.NET, ASP.NET MVC) as well as '
                                          'sampling different frameworks for '
                                          'educational purposes.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>I suppose if I could snap my '
                                          'fingers and get things to exist in '
                                          "django it wouldn't be something "
                                          '<em>new</em> as much as it is '
                                          'official support of:</p>\n'
                                          '<ul>\n'
                                          '<li>Built-in and opinionated way to '
                                          'deal with hierarchical data in the '
                                          'ORM alongside the supporting API '
                                          'for building and traversing them '
                                          'optimally.</li>\n'
                                          '<li>Built-in websockets support. '
                                          'Essentially the <a '
                                          'href="https://channels.readthedocs.io/en/latest/">django-channel</a> '
                                          'experience.</li>\n'
                                          '<li>Built-in ORM support for common '
                                          'constructs like CTEs, and possibly '
                                          'the ability to transition from raw '
                                          'SQL into a queryset pipeline.</li>\n'
                                          '</ul>\n'
                                          "<p>But since we're finger-snapping "
                                          'things to existence, it would be '
                                          'awesome if every component of '
                                          'django (core, orm, templates, '
                                          'forms, "all") could be installed '
                                          'separately in such a way that you '
                                          'could cherry pick what you want to '
                                          'install, so we could dismiss those '
                                          'pesky (cough) '
                                          '<strong>arguments</strong> (cough) '
                                          'about Django being '
                                          '<em>bulky</em>.</p>\n'
                                          '<h4 '
                                          'id="s-what-projects-are-you-working-on-now">What '
                                          'projects are you working on '
                                          'now?</h4>\n'
                                          "<p>I'm involved in numerous "
                                          'projects currently at work, most of '
                                          'which are based on Django, but the '
                                          "one I'm working right now consists "
                                          'of doing integrations and '
                                          'synchronizations with <a '
                                          'href="https://www.sap.com/products/data-cloud/hana/what-is-sap-hana.html">SAP '
                                          'HANA</a> for different modules, in '
                                          'different applications.</p>\n'
                                          "<p>It's quite the challenge, which "
                                          'makes it twice the fun.</p>\n'
                                          '<h4 '
                                          'id="s-which-django-libraries-are-your-favorite-core-or-3rd-party">Which '
                                          'Django libraries are your favorite '
                                          '(core or 3rd party)?</h4>\n'
                                          '<ul>\n'
                                          '<li><a '
                                          'href="https://django-debug-toolbar.readthedocs.io/en/latest/">django-debug-toolbar</a> '
                                          'hands down. It is an absolute beast '
                                          'of a library and a required tool. '
                                          'It is also the lib that influenced '
                                          '<a '
                                          'href="https://dryorm.xterm.info/">DryORM</a></li>\n'
                                          '<li><a '
                                          'href="https://django-extensions.readthedocs.io/en/latest/">django-extensions</a> '
                                          'obviously, for its numerous helper '
                                          'commands (<a '
                                          'href="https://django-extensions.readthedocs.io/en/latest/shell_plus.html#sql-queries">shell_plus '
                                          '--print-sql</a>, <a '
                                          'href="https://django-extensions.readthedocs.io/en/latest/runserver_plus.html">runserver_plus</a>... '
                                          'and much more!)</li>\n'
                                          '<li><a '
                                          'href="https://django-mptt.readthedocs.io/en/latest/">django-mptt</a> '
                                          'while unmaintained, it remains one '
                                          'of my personal favorites for '
                                          "hierarchical data. It's a true "
                                          'piece of art.</li>\n'
                                          '</ul>\n'
                                          "<p>I would like to mention that I'm "
                                          'extremely thankful for any and all '
                                          'core and 3rd Party libraries out '
                                          'there!</p>\n'
                                          '<h4 '
                                          'id="s-what-are-the-top-three-things-in-django-that-you-like">What '
                                          'are the top three things in Django '
                                          'that you like?</h4>\n'
                                          '<p>In no particular order:</p>\n'
                                          '<ul>\n'
                                          '<li>The ORM; We love it, it fits '
                                          'nicely with the rest of the '
                                          'components.</li>\n'
                                          '<li>I feel we should not dismiss '
                                          'what sets Django apart from most '
                                          'frameworks; Its defaults, the '
                                          'conventions, and how opinionated it '
                                          'is; If you avoid '
                                          '<em>overriding</em> the defaults '
                                          "that you get, you'll end up with a "
                                          'codebase that anyone can read, '
                                          'understand and maintain easily. '
                                          '(This is quite subjective and some '
                                          'may very well disagree! ^.^)</li>\n'
                                          '<li>The documentation. Django’s '
                                          'documentation is among the best out '
                                          'there: comprehensive, exhaustive, '
                                          'and incredibly well written.</li>\n'
                                          '</ul>\n'
                                          '<h4 '
                                          'id="s-you-are-helping-a-lot-of-folks-in-django-discord-what-do-you-think-is-needed-to-be-a-good-helper-according-to-you">You '
                                          'are helping a lot of folks in '
                                          'Django Discord, what do you think '
                                          'is needed to be a good helper '
                                          'according to you?</h4>\n'
                                          '<p>First and foremost, I want to '
                                          'highlight what an excellent staff '
                                          'team we have on the <a '
                                          'href="https://chat.djangoproject.com/">Official '
                                          'Django Discord</a>. While I don’t '
                                          'feel I hold a candle to what the '
                                          'rest of the team does daily, we '
                                          'complement each other very '
                                          'well.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>To me, being a good helper '
                                          'means:</p>\n'
                                          '<ul>\n'
                                          '<li>Having patience. You’ve built '
                                          'skills over many years, and not '
                                          'everyone is at the same stage. '
                                          'People will ask unreasonable or '
                                          'incorrect questions, and sometimes '
                                          'they simply won’t listen.</li>\n'
                                          '<li>Guiding people toward figuring '
                                          'things out themselves. Giving a '
                                          'direct solution rarely helps in the '
                                          'long run. There are no scoreboards '
                                          'when it comes to helping '
                                          'others.</li>\n'
                                          '<li>Teaching how to break problems '
                                          'down and reduce noise, especially '
                                          'how to produce the <a '
                                          'href="https://sscce.org/">bare '
                                          'minimum code needed to reproduce an '
                                          'issue.</a></li>\n'
                                          '<li>Point them to <a '
                                          'href="https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/6.0/">the '
                                          'official documentation</a> first, '
                                          'and teaching them how to find '
                                          'answers.</li>\n'
                                          '<li>Staying humble. No one knows '
                                          'everything, and you can always '
                                          'learn from your peers.</li>\n'
                                          '</ul>\n'
                                          '<h4 '
                                          'id="s-dry-orm-is-really-appreciated-what-motivated-you-to-create-the-project">Dry '
                                          'ORM is really appreciated! What '
                                          'motivated you to create the '
                                          'project?</h4>\n'
                                          "<p>Imagine you're having a "
                                          'discussion with a djangonaut friend '
                                          'or colleague about some data '
                                          'modeling, or answering some '
                                          'question or concern they have, or '
                                          'reviewing some ORM code in a '
                                          'repository on github, or helping '
                                          'someone on IRC, Slack, Discord, the '
                                          'forums... or simply you want to do '
                                          'some quick ORM experiment but not '
                                          'disturb your current project. </p>\n'
                                          '<p>The most common ways people deal '
                                          'with this, is by having a '
                                          'throw-away project that they add '
                                          'models to, generate migrations, '
                                          'open the shell, run the queries '
                                          'they want, reset the db if needed, '
                                          'copy the models and the shell code '
                                          'into some code sharing site, then '
                                          'send the link to the recipient. Not '
                                          'to mention needing to store the '
                                          'code they experiment with in either '
                                          'separate scripts or management '
                                          'commands so they can have them as '
                                          'references for later.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>I loved what DDT gave me with '
                                          'the queries transparency, I loved '
                                          'experimenting in the shell with '
                                          '<code>shell_plus --print-sql</code> '
                                          'and I needed to share things '
                                          'online. All of this was cumbersome '
                                          'and that’s when DryORM came into '
                                          'existence, simplifying the entire '
                                          'process into a single code '
                                          'snippet.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>The need grew massively when I '
                                          'became a helper on Official Django '
                                          'Discord and noticed we (Staff) '
                                          'could greatly benefit from having '
                                          'this tool not only to assist '
                                          'others, but share knowledge among '
                                          'ourselves. While I never truly '
                                          'wanted to go <em>public</em> with '
                                          'it, I was encouraged by my peers on '
                                          'Discord to share it and since then, '
                                          "they've been extremely supportive "
                                          'and assisted in its evolution.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>The unexpected thing however, '
                                          'was for DryORM to be used in the <a '
                                          'href="https://code.djangoproject.com/timeline?from=2025-07-18T09%3A17%3A02-05%3A00&amp;precision=second">official '
                                          'code tracker</a>, or the <a '
                                          'href="https://forum.djangoproject.com/t/foreignkey-to-field-doesnt-require-null-false">forums</a>, '
                                          'or even in <a '
                                          'href="https://github.com/django/django/pull/20085#discussion_r2522802667">Github '
                                          "PRs</a>! Ever since, I've decided "
                                          'to put a lot of focus and effort on '
                                          'having features that can support '
                                          'the django contributors in their '
                                          'quest evolve Django.</p>\n'
                                          "<p>So here's a shout-out to "
                                          'everyone that use DryORM!</p>\n'
                                          '<h4 '
                                          'id="s-i-believe-you-are-the-main-maintainer-do-you-need-help-on-something">I '
                                          'believe you are the main '
                                          'maintainer, do you need help on '
                                          'something?</h4>\n'
                                          '<p>Yes, I am and thank you! I think '
                                          'the application has reached a point '
                                          'where new feature releases will '
                                          'slow down, so it’s entering more of '
                                          'a maintenance phase now, which I '
                                          'can manage.</p>\n'
                                          "<p>Hopefully soon we'll have the "
                                          'discord bot executing ORM snippet '
                                          ':-]</p>\n'
                                          '<h4 '
                                          'id="s-what-are-your-hobbies-or-what-do-you-do-when-youre-not-working">What '
                                          'are your hobbies or what do you do '
                                          'when you’re not working?</h4>\n'
                                          "<p>Oh wow, not working, what's that "
                                          'like! :-]</p>\n'
                                          '<p>Early mornings are usually '
                                          'reserved for weight training.\\\n'
                                          'Followed by a long, full '
                                          'workday.\\\n'
                                          'Then escorting and watching the '
                                          'kids at practice.\\\n'
                                          'Evenings are spent with my wife.\\\n'
                                          'Late nights are either light gaming '
                                          'or some tech-related reading and '
                                          'prototyping.\\</p>\n'
                                          '<p>Weekends look very similar, just '
                                          'with many more kids sports '
                                          'matches!</p>\n'
                                          '<h4 '
                                          'id="s-is-there-anything-else-youd-like-to-say">Is '
                                          'there anything else you’d like to '
                                          'say?</h4>\n'
                                          '<p>I want to thank everyone who '
                                          'helped make Django what it is '
                                          'today.</p>\n'
                                          '<p>If you’re reading this and '
                                          'aren’t yet part of the Discord '
                                          'community, <a '
                                          'href="https://chat.djangoproject.com/">I '
                                          'invite you to join us</a>! You’ll '
                                          'find many like-minded people to '
                                          'discuss your interests with. '
                                          'Whether you’re there to help, get '
                                          'help, or just hang around, it’s a '
                                          'fun place to be.</p>\n'
                                          '<hr />\n'
                                          '<p><strong>Thank you for doing the '
                                          'interview, Omar!</strong></p>'},
              'title': 'DSF member of the month - Omar Abou Mrad',
